The increase in the share of renewables (including traditional biomass
                              1


                              1
                              Traditional biomass refers to residential consumption of solid biofuels (wood, charcoal, agricultural residues, and animal dung) burned with basic techniques, such as traditional open cookstoves and fireplaces in non-OECD countries. In OECD countries, biomass (split logs) is used in fireplaces, but they are not covered in this analysis. Although in principle, the focus of renewables for biomass is to encourage modern generation and use.
                           ) in total final energy consumption (TFEC) has been relatively small since 2015, rising to 19.1 % in 2020 from 16.7 % (Fig. 2
                           ). The fastest growth in renewables was in the power sector accounting for about 25 % of global electricity consumption with lower deployment of modern renewables in the heat and transport sectors. Whilst transport has the lowest share of renewables, REN21 [8] reports that this sector has one of the fastest rates of renewable energy adoption (more than 7 % yearly) along with agriculture. Traditional biomass still provides 12 % of global heat consumption, and modern renewables 9.2 %. For transport the share of renewables was just 3.3 %, mainly as liquid biofuels, with 60 % of consumption coming from the US and Brazil. The distribution of renewables and the role of traditional biomass differs regionally. Traditional use of biomass is concentrated in sub-Saharan Africa and Asia, which is gradually being replaced by gaseous fuels and modern renewables. Similar trends are observed in Central and Southern Asia and to some extent Latin America and the Caribbean regions.
